df = pl.read_csv("dataset/cleaned_data.csv") \
    .filter(pl.col("StationId").is_in(["DL002", "DL019", "DL028", "DL031"])) \
    .with_columns(pl.col('Date').str.to_datetime().cast(pl.Date)) \
    .filter(pl.col("Date") >= pl.lit("2017-11-01").cast(pl.Date)) \
    .filter(pl.col("Date") <= pl.lit("2020-06-30").cast(pl.Date)) \
    .with_columns(pl.col("Date").dt.month().alias("Month")) \
    .with_columns(pl.col("Date").dt.year().alias("Year")) \
    .with_columns(pl.col("Date").dt.day().alias("Day")) \
    .with_columns(pl.concat_str([pl.col("Year"), pl.col("Month")], separator="-").alias("Year-Month")) \
    .sort("Year", "Month", "Day", "StationId")

date_range = list(dict.fromkeys(df["Year-Month"].to_list()))

df_monthly = df.group_by("StationId", "Year-Month", "Month", "Year") \
    .agg([pl.col(metric).mean().alias(metric) for metric in air_metrics]) \
    .sort("Year", "Month")

def get_stats(air_metric):
    return df.group_by("StationId").agg([
        pl.col(air_metric).mean().alias(air_metric+f"_mean"),
        pl.col(air_metric).median().alias(air_metric+"_median"),
        pl.col(air_metric).std().alias(air_metric+"_std"),
        pl.col(air_metric).var().alias(air_metric+"_var"),
        pl.col(air_metric).min().alias(air_metric+"_min"),
        pl.col(air_metric).max().alias(air_metric+"_max")
    ]).sort("StationId")

for air_metric in air_metrics:
    print(get_stats(air_metric))

In[9]:
def plot_time_series(df, x, frequency, rotate=False):
    count = 0
    for air_metric in air_metrics:
        plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
        sns.lineplot(
            data=df.sort("StationId"), 
            x=x, 
            y=air_metric, 
            hue='StationId',
            palette = colors
        )
        
        plt.title(f'Time Series of {air_metric} at 4 Different Stations in Delhi ({frequency})')
        plt.ylabel(air_metric + f" ({units[count]})")
        plt.xlabel("")
        if rotate:
            plt.xticks(rotation=45)
        plt.tight_layout()
        plt.show()
        count += 1

    fig.legend(handles=color_patches, loc='upper right', title="Stations", bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), bbox_transform=plt.gcf().transFigure)
    fig.suptitle(f"{metric} ({units[u_count]}) in Delhi from 2017/10 - 2020/07", fontsize=16)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

In[13]:
def plot_heatmap(corr_df, labels, title):

    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    sns.heatmap(corr_df, annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', vmin=-1, vmax=1, linewidths=0.5,
                xticklabels=labels, yticklabels=labels)
    plt.title(title, fontsize=14)
    plt.show()

from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
import numpy as np
from scipy import stats

# Extract independent (X) and dependent (y) variables
X = station_data.select('TotalDays').to_numpy()
y = station_data.select('PM2.5').to_numpy()

# Fit the linear regression model
model = LinearRegression()
model.fit(X, y)

# Get the coefficients
b0 = model.intercept_[0]  # Intercept
b1 = model.coef_[0][0]    # Slope

# Predict PM2.5 values
y_pred = model.predict(X)

# Calculate residuals
residuals = y.flatten() - y_pred.flatten()

# Calculate standard error of the slope
n = len(y)
se_b1 = np.sqrt(np.sum(residuals**2) / (n - 2)) / np.sqrt(np.sum((X - np.mean(X))**2))

# Calculate t-statistic for b1
t_statistic = b1 / se_b1

# Calculate p-value
p_value = 2 * (1 - stats.t.cdf(np.abs(t_statistic), df=n-2))

# Significance level
alpha = 0.01

# Print the results
print(f"Model: Yi = b0 + b1*ti + i (Y = PM2.5 levels)")
print(f'Null hypothesis:  b1 = 0, i.e. The PM2.5 levels at Station DL028 have not changed over time \n')
print(f"Intercept (b0): {b0}")
print(f"Slope (b1): {b1}")
print(f"T-statistic: {t_statistic}")
print(f"P-value: {p_value}\n")

# Check if we reject or fail to reject the null hypothesis
if p_value < alpha:
    print(f"We reject the null hypothesis at significance level {alpha}: b1 is significantly different from 0")
else:
    print(f"We fail to reject the null hypothesis at significance level {alpha}: b1 is not significantly different from 0")
